# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rowhammer-defense
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] While most DRAM memory cell designs use a capacitor and transistor, some only use two transistors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In the designs where a capacitor is used, the capacitor can either be charged or discharged; these two states are taken to represent the two values of a bit, conventionally called 0 and 1.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The electric charge on the capacitors gradually leaks away; without intervention, the data on the capacitor would soon be lost.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] To prevent this, DRAM requires an external memory refresh circuit which periodically rewrites the data in the capacitors, restoring them to their original charge.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This refresh process is the defining characteristic of dynamic random-access memory, in contrast to static random-access memory (SRAM) which does not require data to be refreshed.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Unlike flash memory, DRAM is volatile memory (as opposed to non-volatile memory), since it loses its data quickly when power is removed.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] However, DRAM does exhibit limited data remanence.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] DRAM typically takes the form of an integrated circuit chip, which can consist of dozens to billions of DRAM memory cells.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] DRAM chips are widely used in digital electronics where low-cost, high-capacity computer memory is required.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] One of the largest applications for DRAM is the *main memory* (colloquially called the RAM) in modern computers and graphics cards (where the main memory is called the *graphics memory*).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] It is also used in many portable devices and video game consoles.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In contrast, SRAM, which is faster and more expensive than DRAM, is typically used where speed is of greater concern than cost and size, such as the cache memories in processors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The need to refresh DRAM demands more complicated circuitry and timing than SRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This complexity is offset by the structural simplicity of DRAM memory cells: only one transistor and a capacitor are required per bit, compared to four or six transistors in SRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This allows DRAM to reach very high densities with a simultaneous reduction in cost per bit.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Refreshing the data consumes power, causing a variety of techniques to be used to manage the overall power consumption.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] For this reason, DRAM usually needs to operate with a memory controller; the memory controller needs to know DRAM parameters, especially memory timings, to initialize DRAMs, which may be different depending on different DRAM manufacturers and part numbers.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] DRAM had a 47% increase in the price-per-bit in 2017, the largest jump in 30 years since the 45% jump in 1988.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In 2018, a "key characteristic of the DRAM market is that there are currently only three major suppliers — Micron Technology, SK Hynix and Samsung Electronics" that are "keeping a pretty tight rein on their capacity".
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] DRAM (DDR4, DDR, and flash memory/NAND) price has in early 2026 "experienced compounded increases, some exceeding 200%, since early 2025 .. [because of] unprecedented demand coming from the AI sector ..
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] HBM is crowding out commodity DRAM capacity.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Other manufacturers make and sell DIMMs but not the DRAM chips in them, such as Kingston Technology, and some manufacturers sell stacked DRAM (used e.g. in the fastest supercomputers on the exascale) separately such as Viking Technology.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Others sell such integrated into other products, such as Fujitsu into its CPUs, AMD in GPUs, and Nvidia, with HBM2 in some of their GPU chips.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The cryptanalytic machine code-named *Aquarius* used at Bletchley Park during World War II incorporated a hard-wired dynamic memory.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Paper tape was read and the characters on it "were remembered in a dynamic store".
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The store used a large bank of capacitors, which were either charged or not, a charged capacitor representing cross (1) and an uncharged capacitor dot (0).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Since the charge gradually leaked away, a periodic pulse was applied to top up those still charged (hence the term 'dynamic')".
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In November 1965, Toshiba introduced a bipolar dynamic RAM for its electronic calculator Toscal BC-1411.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In 1966, Tomohisa Yoshimaru and Hiroshi Komikawa from Toshiba applied for a Japanese patent of a memory circuit composed of several transistors and a capacitor, in 1967 they applied for a patent in the US.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The earliest forms of DRAM mentioned above used bipolar transistors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] While it offered improved performance over magnetic-core memory, bipolar DRAM could not compete with the lower price of the then-dominant magnetic-core memory.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Capacitors had also been used for earlier memory schemes, such as the drum of the Atanasoff–Berry Computer, the Williams tube and the Selectron tube.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Robert Dennard invented modern DRAM architecture in which there's a single MOS transistor per capacitor, at the IBM Thomas J.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Watson Research Center, while he was working on MOS memory and was trying to create an alternative to SRAM which required six MOS transistors for each bit of data.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] While examining the characteristics of MOS technology, he found it was capable of building capacitors, and that storing a charge or no charge on the MOS capacitor could represent the 1 and 0 of a bit, while the MOS transistor could control writing the charge to the capacitor.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This led to his development of the single-transistor MOS DRAM memory cell.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] He filed a patent in 1967, and was granted U.S. patent number 3,387,286 in 1968.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] MOS memory offered higher performance, was cheaper, and consumed less power, than magnetic-core memory.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] MOS DRAM chips were commercialized in 1969 by Advanced Memory Systems, Inc., of Sunnyvale, CA.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This 1024 bit chip was sold to Honeywell, Raytheon, Wang Laboratories, and others.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The same year, Honeywell asked Intel to make a DRAM using a three-transistor cell that they had developed.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This became the Intel 1102 in early 1970.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] However, the 1102 had many problems, prompting Intel to begin work on their own improved design, in secrecy to avoid conflict with Honeywell.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This became the first commercially available DRAM, the Intel 1103, in October 1970, despite initial problems with low yield until the fifth revision of the masks.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The 1103 was designed by Joel Karp and laid out by Pat Earhart.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The masks were cut by Barbara Maness and Judy Garcia.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] MOS memory overtook magnetic-core memory as the dominant memory technology in the early 1970s.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The first DRAM with multiplexed row and column address lines was the Mostek MK4096 4 Kbit DRAM designed by Robert Proebsting and introduced in 1973.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This addressing scheme uses the same address pins to receive the low half and the high half of the address of the memory cell being referenced, switching between the two halves on alternating bus cycles.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This was a radical advance, effectively halving the number of address lines required, which enabled it to fit into packages with fewer pins, a cost advantage that grew with every jump in memory size.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The MK4096 proved to be a very robust design for customer applications.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] At the 16 Kbit density, the cost advantage increased; the 16 Kbit Mostek MK4116 DRAM, introduced in 1976, achieved greater than 75% worldwide DRAM market share.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] However, as density increased to 64 Kbit in the early 1980s, Mostek and other US manufacturers were overtaken by Japanese DRAM manufacturers, which dominated the US and worldwide markets during the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Early in 1985, Gordon Moore decided to withdraw Intel from producing DRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] By 1986, many, but not all, United States chip makers had stopped making DRAMs.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Micron Technology and Texas Instruments continued to produce them commercially, and IBM produced them for internal use.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Prices for the 64K product plummeted to as low as 35 cents apiece from $3.50 within 18 months, with disastrous financial consequences for some U.S. firms.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] On 4 December 1985 the US Commerce Department's International Trade Administration ruled in favor of the complaint.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Synchronous dynamic random-access memory (SDRAM) was developed by Samsung.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The first commercial SDRAM chip was the Samsung KM48SL2000, which had a capacity of 16 Mbit, and was introduced in 1992.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The first commercial DDR SDRAM (double data rate SDRAM) memory chip was Samsung's 64 Mbit DDR SDRAM chip, released in 1998.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Later, in 2001, Japanese DRAM makers accused Korean DRAM manufacturers of dumping.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In 2002, the United States Department of Justice began an investigation which ultimately found several computer manufacturers guilty of DRAM price fixing.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] DRAM is usually arranged in a rectangular array of charge storage cells consisting of one capacitor and transistor per data bit.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The figure to the right shows a simple example with a four-by-four cell matrix.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Some DRAM matrices are many thousands of cells in height and width.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The long horizontal lines connecting each row are known as word-lines.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Each column of cells is composed of two bit-lines, each connected to every other storage cell in the column (the illustration to the right does not include this important detail).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] They are generally known as the *+* and *−* bit lines.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] A sense amplifier is essentially a pair of cross-connected inverters between the bit-lines.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The first inverter is connected with input from the + bit-line and output to the − bit-line.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The second inverter's input is from the − bit-line with output to the + bit-line.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This results in positive feedback which stabilizes after one bit-line is fully at its highest voltage and the other bit-line is at the lowest possible voltage.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The bit-lines are precharged to exactly equal voltages that are in between high and low logic levels (e.g., 0.5 V if the two levels are 0 and 1 V).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The bit-lines are physically symmetrical to keep the capacitance equal, and therefore at this time their voltages are equal.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Because the bit-lines are relatively long, they have enough capacitance to maintain the precharged voltage for a brief time.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The desired row's word-line is then driven high to connect a cell's storage capacitor to its bit-line.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This causes the transistor to conduct, transferring charge from the storage cell to the connected bit-line (if the stored value is 1) or from the connected bit-line to the storage cell (if the stored value is 0).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] As the other bit-line holds 0.50 V there is a small voltage difference between the two twisted bit-lines.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The sense amplifiers are now connected to the bit-lines pairs.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Positive feedback then occurs from the cross-connected inverters, thereby amplifying the small voltage difference between the odd and even row bit-lines of a particular column until one bit line is fully at the lowest voltage and the other is at the maximum high voltage.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Once this has happened, the row is *open* (the desired cell data is available).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] All storage cells in the open row are sensed simultaneously, and the sense amplifier outputs latched.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] A column address then selects which latch bit to connect to the external data bus.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Reads of different columns in the same row can be performed without a row opening delay because, for the open row, all data has already been sensed and latched.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] While reading of columns in an open row is occurring, current is flowing back up the bit-lines from the output of the sense amplifiers and recharging the storage cells.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This reinforces (i.e. refreshes) the charge in the storage cell by increasing the voltage in the storage capacitor if it was charged to begin with, or by keeping it discharged if it was empty.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Note that due to the length of the bit-lines there is a fairly long propagation delay for the charge to be transferred back to the cell's capacitor.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This takes significant time past the end of sense amplification, and thus overlaps with one or more column reads.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] When done with reading all the columns in the current open row, the word-line is switched off to disconnect the storage cell capacitors (the row is closed) from the bit-lines.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The sense amplifier is switched off, and the bit-lines are precharged again.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] To store data, a row is opened and a given column's sense amplifier is temporarily forced to the desired high or low-voltage state, thus causing the bit-line to charge or discharge the cell storage capacitor to the desired value.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Due to the sense amplifier's positive feedback configuration, it will hold a bit-line at stable voltage even after the forcing voltage is removed.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] During a write to a particular cell, all the columns in a row are sensed simultaneously just as during reading, so although only a single column's storage-cell capacitor charge is changed, the entire row is refreshed (written back in), as illustrated in the figure to the right.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Typically, manufacturers specify that each row must be refreshed every 64 ms or less, as defined by the JEDEC standard.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Some systems refresh every row in a burst of activity involving all rows every 64 ms.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Other systems refresh one row at a time staggered throughout the 64 ms interval.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] For example, a system with 213 = 8,192 rows would require a staggered refresh rate of one row every 7.8 μs which is 64 ms divided by 8,192 rows.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] A few real-time systems refresh a portion of memory at a time determined by an external timer function that governs the operation of the rest of a system, such as the vertical blanking interval that occurs every 10–20 ms in video equipment.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The row address of the row that will be refreshed next is maintained by external logic or a counter within the DRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] A system that provides the row address (and the refresh command) does so to have greater control over when to refresh and which row to refresh.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This is done to minimize conflicts with memory accesses, since such a system has both knowledge of the memory access patterns and the refresh requirements of the DRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] When the row address is supplied by a counter within the DRAM, the system relinquishes control over which row is refreshed and only provides the refresh command.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Some modern DRAMs are capable of self-refresh; no external logic is required to instruct the DRAM to refresh or to provide a row address.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Under some conditions, most of the data in DRAM can be recovered even if the DRAM has not been refreshed for several minutes.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Many parameters are required to fully describe the timing of DRAM operation.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Thus, the generally quoted number is the /RAS low to valid data out time.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This is the time to open a row, settle the sense amplifiers, and deliver the selected column data to the output.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This is also the minimum /RAS low time, which includes the time for the amplified data to be delivered back to recharge the cells.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The time to read additional bits from an open page is much less, defined by the /CAS to /CAS cycle time.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The quoted number is the clearest way to compare between the performance of different DRAM memories, as it sets the slower limit regardless of the row length or page size.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Bigger arrays forcibly result in larger bit line capacitance and longer propagation delays, which cause this time to increase as the sense amplifier settling time is dependent on both the capacitance as well as the propagation latency.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This is countered in modern DRAM chips by instead integrating many more complete DRAM arrays within a single chip, to accommodate more capacity without becoming too slow.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] When such a RAM is accessed by clocked logic, the times are generally rounded up to the nearest clock cycle.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] For example, when accessed by a 100 MHz state machine (i.e. a 10 ns clock), the 50 ns DRAM can perform the first read in five clock cycles, and additional reads within the same page every two clock cycles.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This was generally described as "5-2-2-2" timing, as bursts of four reads within a page were common.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] When describing synchronous memory, timing is described by clock cycle counts separated by hyphens.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] These numbers represent *t*CL-*t*RCD-*t*RP-*t*RAS in multiples of the DRAM clock cycle time.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Note that this is half of the data transfer rate when double data rate signaling is used.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] JEDEC standard PC3200 timing is 3-4-4-8 with a 200 MHz clock, while premium-priced high performance PC3200 DDR DRAM DIMM might be operated at 2-2-2-5 timing.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Minimum random access time has improved from *t*RAC = 50 ns to *t*RCD + *t*CL = 22.5 ns, and even the premium 20 ns variety is only 2.5 times faster than the asynchronous DRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] CAS latency has improved even less, from *t*CAC = 13 ns to 10 ns.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] However, the DDR3 memory does achieve 32 times higher bandwidth; due to internal pipelining and wide data paths, it can output two words every 1.25 ns (1600 Mword/s), while the EDO DRAM can output one word per *t*PC = 20 ns (50 Mword/s).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Each bit of data in a DRAM is stored as a positive or negative electrical charge in a capacitive structure.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The structure providing the capacitance, as well as the transistors that control access to it, is collectively referred to as a *DRAM cell*.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] They are the fundamental building block in DRAM arrays.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Multiple DRAM memory cell variants exist, but the most commonly used variant in modern DRAMs is the one-transistor, one-capacitor (1T1C) cell.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The transistor is used to admit current into the capacitor during writes, and to discharge the capacitor during reads.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The access transistor is designed to maximize drive strength and minimize transistor-transistor leakage (Kenner, p.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The capacitor has two terminals, one of which is connected to its access transistor, and the other to either ground or VCC/2.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In modern DRAMs, the latter case is more common, since it allows faster operation.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In modern DRAMs, a voltage of +VCC/2 across the capacitor is required to store a logic one; and a voltage of −VCC/2 across the capacitor is required to store a logic zero.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The resultant charge is ${\textstyle Q=\pm {V_{CC} \over 2}\cdot C}$ , where *Q* is the charge in coulombs and *C* is the capacitance in farads.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Reading or writing a logic one requires the wordline be driven to a voltage greater than the sum of VCC and the access transistor's threshold voltage (VTH).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This voltage is called *VCC pumped* (VCCP).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The time required to discharge a capacitor thus depends on what logic value is stored in the capacitor.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] A capacitor containing logic one begins to discharge when the voltage at the access transistor's gate terminal is above VCCP.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] If the capacitor contains a logic zero, it begins to discharge when the gate terminal voltage is above VTH.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Up until the mid-1980s, the capacitors in DRAM cells were co-planar with the access transistor (they were constructed on the surface of the substrate), thus they were referred to as *planar* capacitors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The drive to increase both density and, to a lesser extent, performance, required denser designs.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This was strongly motivated by economics, a major consideration for DRAM devices, especially commodity DRAMs.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The minimization of DRAM cell area can produce a denser device and lower the cost per bit of storage.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Starting in the mid-1980s, the capacitor was moved above or below the silicon substrate in order to meet these objectives.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] DRAM cells featuring capacitors above the substrate are referred to as *stacked* or *folded plate* capacitors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Those with capacitors buried beneath the substrate surface are referred to as *trench* capacitors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In the 2000s, manufacturers were sharply divided by the type of capacitor used in their DRAMs and the relative cost and long-term scalability of both designs have been the subject of extensive debate.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The majority of DRAMs, from major manufacturers such as Hynix, Micron Technology, Samsung Electronics use the stacked capacitor structure, whereas smaller manufacturers such as Nanya Technology use the trench capacitor structure (Jacob, pp.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The capacitor in the stacked capacitor scheme is constructed above the surface of the substrate.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The capacitor is constructed from an oxide-nitride-oxide (ONO) dielectric sandwiched in between two layers of polysilicon plates (the top plate is shared by all DRAM cells in an IC), and its shape can be a rectangle, a cylinder, or some other more complex shape.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] There are two basic variations of the stacked capacitor, based on its location relative to the bitline—capacitor-under-bitline (CUB) and capacitor-over-bitline (COB).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In the former, the capacitor is underneath the bitline, which is usually made of metal, and the bitline has a polysilicon contact that extends downwards to connect it to the access transistor's source terminal.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In the latter, the capacitor is constructed above the bitline, which is almost always made of polysilicon, but is otherwise identical to the COB variation.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The advantage the COB variant possesses is the ease of fabricating the contact between the bitline and the access transistor's source as it is physically close to the substrate surface.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] However, this requires the active area to be laid out at a 45-degree angle when viewed from above, which makes it difficult to ensure that the capacitor contact does not touch the bitline.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] CUB cells avoid this, but suffer from difficulties in inserting contacts in between bitlines, since the size of features this close to the surface are at or near the minimum feature size of the process technology (Kenner, pp.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The trench capacitor is constructed by etching a deep hole into the silicon substrate.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The substrate volume surrounding the hole is then heavily doped to produce a buried n+ plate with low resistance.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] A layer of oxide-nitride-oxide dielectric is grown or deposited, and finally the hole is filled by depositing doped polysilicon, which forms the top plate of the capacitor.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The top of the capacitor is connected to the access transistor's drain terminal via a polysilicon strap (Kenner, pp.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] A trench capacitor's depth-to-width ratio in DRAMs of the mid-2000s can exceed 50:1 (Jacob, p.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Trench capacitors have numerous advantages.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Since the capacitor is buried in the bulk of the substrate instead of lying on its surface, the area it occupies can be minimized to what is required to connect it to the access transistor's drain terminal without decreasing the capacitor's size, and thus capacitance (Jacob, pp.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Alternatively, the capacitance can be increased by etching a deeper hole without any increase to surface area (Kenner, p.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Another advantage of the trench capacitor is that its structure is under the layers of metal interconnect, allowing them to be more easily made planar, which enables it to be integrated in a logic-optimized process technology, which have many levels of interconnect above the substrate.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The fact that the capacitor is under the logic means that it is constructed before the transistors are.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This allows high-temperature processes to fabricate the capacitors, which would otherwise degrade the logic transistors and their performance.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This makes trench capacitors suitable for constructing embedded DRAM (eDRAM) (Jacob, p.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Disadvantages of trench capacitors are difficulties in reliably constructing the capacitor's structures within deep holes and in connecting the capacitor to the access transistor's drain terminal (Kenner, p.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] First-generation DRAM ICs (those with capacities of 1 Kbit), such as the archetypical Intel 1103, used a three-transistor, one-capacitor (3T1C) DRAM cell with separate read and write circuitry.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The write wordline drove a write transistor which connected the capacitor to the write bitline just as in the 1T1C cell, but there was a separate read wordline and read transistor which connected an amplifier transistor to the read bitline.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] By the second generation, the drive to reduce cost by fitting the same amount of bits in a smaller area led to the almost universal adoption of the 1T1C DRAM cell, although a couple of devices with 4 and 16 Kbit capacities continued to use the 3T1C cell for performance reasons (Kenner, p.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] These performance advantages included, most significantly, the ability to read the state stored by the capacitor without discharging it, avoiding the need to write back what was read out (non-destructive read).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] A second performance advantage relates to the 3T1C cell's separate transistors for reading and writing; the memory controller can exploit this feature to perform atomic read-modify-writes, where a value is read, modified, and then written back as a single, indivisible operation (Jacob, p.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The one-transistor, zero-capacitor (1T, or 1T0C) DRAM cell has been a topic of research since the late-1990s.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] *1T DRAM* is a different way of constructing the basic DRAM memory cell, distinct from the classic one-transistor/one-capacitor (1T/1C) DRAM cell, which is also sometimes referred to as *1T DRAM*, particularly in comparison to the 3T and 4T DRAM which it replaced in the 1970s.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In 1T DRAM cells, the bit of data is still stored in a capacitive region controlled by a transistor, but this capacitance is no longer provided by a separate capacitor.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] 1T DRAM is a "capacitorless" bit cell design that stores data using the parasitic body capacitance that is inherent to silicon on insulator (SOI) transistors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Considered a nuisance in logic design, this floating body effect can be used for data storage.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This gives 1T DRAM cells the greatest density as well as allowing easier integration with high-performance logic circuits since they are constructed with the same SOI process technologies.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Refreshing of cells remains necessary, but unlike with 1T1C DRAM, reads in 1T DRAM are non-destructive; the stored charge causes a detectable shift in the threshold voltage of the transistor.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Performance-wise, access times are significantly better than capacitor-based DRAMs, but slightly worse than SRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] There are several types of 1T DRAMs: the commercialized Z-RAM from Innovative Silicon, the TTRAM from Renesas and the A-RAM from the UGR/CNRS consortium.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] DRAM cells are laid out in a regular rectangular, grid-like pattern to facilitate their control and access via wordlines and bitlines.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The physical layout of the DRAM cells in an array is typically designed so that two adjacent DRAM cells in a column share a single bitline contact to reduce their area.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] DRAM cell area is given as *n*F2, where *n* is a number derived from the DRAM cell design, and *F* is the smallest feature size of a given process technology.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This scheme permits comparison of DRAM size over different process technology generations, as DRAM cell area scales at linear or near-linear rates with respect to feature size.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The typical area for modern DRAM cells varies between 6–8 F2.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The horizontal wire, the wordline, is connected to the gate terminal of every access transistor in its row.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The vertical bitline is connected to the source terminal of the transistors in its column.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The lengths of the wordlines and bitlines are limited.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The wordline length is limited by the desired performance of the array, since propagation time of the signal that must traverse the wordline is determined by the RC time constant.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The bitline length is limited by its capacitance (which increases with length), which must be kept within a range for proper sensing (as DRAMs operate by sensing the charge of the capacitor released onto the bitline).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Bitline length is also limited by the amount of operating current the DRAM can draw and by how power can be dissipated, since these two characteristics are largely determined by the charging and discharging of the bitline.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Sense amplifiers are required to read the state contained in the DRAM cells.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] When the access transistor is activated, the electrical charge in the capacitor is shared with the bitline.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The bitline's capacitance is much greater than that of the capacitor (approximately ten times).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Thus, the change in bitline voltage is minute.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Sense amplifiers are required to resolve the voltage differential into the levels specified by the logic signaling system.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Modern DRAMs use differential sense amplifiers, and are accompanied by requirements as to how the DRAM arrays are constructed.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Differential sense amplifiers work by driving their outputs to opposing extremes based on the relative voltages on pairs of bitlines.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The sense amplifiers function effectively and efficiently only if the capacitance and voltages of these bitline pairs are closely matched.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Besides ensuring that the lengths of the bitlines and the number of DRAM cells attached to them are equal, two basic architectures to array design have emerged to provide for the requirements of the sense amplifiers: open and folded bitline arrays.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The first generation (1 Kbit) DRAM ICs, up until the 64 Kbit generation (and some 256 Kbit generation devices) had open bitline array architectures.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In these architectures, the bitlines are divided into multiple segments, and the differential sense amplifiers are placed in between bitline segments.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Because the sense amplifiers are placed between bitline segments, to route their outputs outside the array, an additional layer of interconnect placed above those used to construct the wordlines and bitlines is required.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The DRAM cells that are on the edges of the array do not have adjacent segments.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Since the differential sense amplifiers require identical capacitance and bitline lengths from both segments, dummy bitline segments are provided.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The advantage of the open bitline array is a smaller array area, although this advantage is slightly diminished by the dummy bitline segments.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The disadvantage that caused the near disappearance of this architecture is the inherent vulnerability to noise, which affects the effectiveness of the differential sense amplifiers.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Since each bitline segment does not have any spatial relationship to the other, it is likely that noise would affect only one of the two bitline segments.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The folded bitline array architecture routes bitlines in pairs throughout the array.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The close proximity of the paired bitlines provide superior common-mode noise rejection characteristics over open bitline arrays.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The folded bitline array architecture began appearing in DRAM ICs during the mid-1980s, beginning with the 256 Kbit generation.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This architecture is favored in modern DRAM ICs for its superior noise immunity.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This architecture is referred to as *folded* because it takes its basis from the open array architecture from the perspective of the circuit schematic.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The folded array architecture appears to remove DRAM cells in alternate pairs (because two DRAM cells share a single bitline contact) from a column, then move the DRAM cells from an adjacent column into the voids.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The location where the bitline twists occupies additional area.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] To minimize area overhead, engineers select the simplest and most area-minimal twisting scheme that is able to reduce noise under the specified limit.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] As process technology improves to reduce minimum feature sizes, the signal to noise problem worsens, since coupling between adjacent metal wires is inversely proportional to their pitch.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The array folding and bitline twisting schemes that are used must increase in complexity in order to maintain sufficient noise reduction.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Schemes that have desirable noise immunity characteristics for a minimal impact in area is the topic of current research (Kenner, p.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Advances in process technology could result in open bitline array architectures being favored if it is able to offer better long-term area efficiencies; since folded array architectures require increasingly complex folding schemes to match any advance in process technology.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The relationship between process technology, array architecture, and area efficiency is an active area of research.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The first DRAM integrated circuits did not have any redundancy.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] An integrated circuit with a defective DRAM cell would be discarded.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Beginning with the 64 Kbit generation, DRAM arrays have included spare rows and columns to improve yields.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Spare rows and columns provide tolerance of minor fabrication defects which have caused a small number of rows or columns to be inoperable.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The defective rows and columns are physically disconnected from the rest of the array by triggering a programmable fuse or by cutting the wire by a laser.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The spare rows or columns are substituted in by remapping logic in the row and column decoders (Jacob, pp.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Electrical or magnetic interference inside a computer system can cause a single bit of DRAM to spontaneously flip to the opposite state.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The majority of one-off ("soft") errors in DRAM chips occur as a result of background radiation, chiefly neutrons from cosmic ray secondaries, which may change the contents of one or more memory cells or interfere with the circuitry used to read/write them.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The problem can be mitigated by using redundant memory bits and additional circuitry that use these bits to detect and correct soft errors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In most cases, the detection and correction are performed by the memory controller; sometimes, the required logic is transparently implemented within DRAM chips or modules, enabling the ECC memory functionality for otherwise ECC-incapable systems.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The extra memory bits are used to record parity and to enable missing data to be reconstructed by error-correcting code (ECC).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Parity allows the detection of all single-bit errors (actually, any odd number of wrong bits).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The most common error-correcting code, a SECDED Hamming code, allows a single-bit error to be corrected and, in the usual configuration, with an extra parity bit, double-bit errors to be detected.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Recent studies give widely varying error rates with over seven orders of magnitude difference, ranging from 10−10−10−17 error/bit·h, roughly one bit error, per hour, per gigabyte of memory to one bit error, per century, per gigabyte of memory.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] A 2010 study at the University of Rochester also gave evidence that a substantial fraction of memory errors are intermittent hard errors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Although dynamic memory is only specified and *guaranteed* to retain its contents when supplied with power and refreshed every short period of time (often 64 ms), the memory cell capacitors often retain their values for significantly longer time, particularly at low temperatures.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Under some conditions most of the data in DRAM can be recovered even if it has not been refreshed for several minutes.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This property can be used to circumvent security and recover data stored in the main memory that is assumed to be destroyed at power-down.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The computer could be quickly rebooted, and the contents of the main memory read out; or by removing a computer's memory modules, cooling them to prolong data remanence, then transferring them to a different computer to be read out.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Such an attack was demonstrated to circumvent popular disk encryption systems, such as the open source TrueCrypt, Microsoft's BitLocker Drive Encryption, and Apple's FileVault.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This type of attack against a computer is often called a cold boot attack.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Dynamic memory, by definition, requires periodic refresh.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Furthermore, reading dynamic memory is a destructive operation, requiring a recharge of the storage cells in the row that has been read.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] If these processes are imperfect, a read operation can cause soft errors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In particular, there is a risk that some charge can leak between nearby cells, causing the refresh or read of one row to cause a *disturbance error* in an adjacent or even nearby row.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The awareness of disturbance errors dates back to the first commercially available DRAM in the early 1970s (the Intel 1103).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Despite the mitigation techniques employed by manufacturers, commercial researchers proved in a 2014 analysis that commercially available DDR3 DRAM chips manufactured in 2012 and 2013 are susceptible to disturbance errors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The associated side effect that led to observed bit flips has been dubbed *row hammer*.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Dynamic RAM ICs can be packaged in molded epoxy cases, with an internal lead frame for interconnections between the silicon die and the package leads.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The original IBM PC design used ICs, including those for DRAM, packaged in dual in-line packages (DIP), soldered directly to the main board or mounted in sockets.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] As memory density skyrocketed, the DIP package was no longer practical.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] For convenience in handling, several dynamic RAM integrated circuits may be mounted on a single memory module, allowing installation of 16-bit, 32-bit or 64-bit wide memory in a single unit, without the requirement for the installer to insert multiple individual integrated circuits.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Memory modules may include additional devices for parity checking or error correction.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Over the evolution of desktop computers, several standardized types of memory module have been developed.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Laptop computers, game consoles, and specialized devices may have their own formats of memory modules not interchangeable with standard desktop parts for packaging or proprietary reasons.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] DRAM that is integrated into an integrated circuit designed in a logic-optimized process (such as an application-specific integrated circuit, microprocessor, or an entire system on a chip) is called *embedded DRAM* (eDRAM).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Embedded DRAM requires DRAM cell designs that can be fabricated without preventing the fabrication of fast-switching transistors used in high-performance logic, and modification of the basic logic-optimized process technology to accommodate the process steps required to build DRAM cell structures.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Since the fundamental DRAM cell and array has maintained the same basic structure for many years, the types of DRAM are mainly distinguished by the many different interfaces for communicating with DRAM chips.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] The original DRAM, now known by the retronym *asynchronous DRAM* was the first type of DRAM in use.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] From its origins in the late 1960s, it was commonplace in computing up until around 1997, when it was mostly replaced by *synchronous DRAM*.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] In the present day, manufacture of asynchronous RAM is relatively rare.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] An asynchronous DRAM chip has power connections, some number of address inputs (typically 12), and a few (typically one or four) bidirectional data lines.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] This interface provides direct control of internal timing: when RAS is driven low, a CAS cycle must not be attempted until the sense amplifiers have sensed the memory state, and RAS must not be returned high until the storage cells have been refreshed.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] When RAS is driven high, it must be held high long enough for precharging to complete.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Although the DRAM is asynchronous, the signals are typically generated by a clocked memory controller, which limits their timing to multiples of the controller's clock cycle.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Classic asynchronous DRAM is refreshed by opening each row in turn.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] The refresh cycles are distributed across the entire refresh interval in such a way that all rows are refreshed within the required interval.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] At the end of the required amount of time, RAS must return high.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] This can be done by supplying a row address and pulsing RAS low; it is not necessary to perform any CAS cycles.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] An external counter is needed to iterate over the row addresses in turn.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] In some designs, the CPU handled RAM refresh.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] The Zilog Z80 is perhaps the best known example, as it has an internal row counter R which supplies the address for a special refresh cycle generated after each instruction fetch.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] In other systems, especially home computers, refresh was handled by the video circuitry as a side effect of its periodic scan of the frame buffer.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] For convenience, the counter was quickly incorporated into the DRAM chips themselves.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] If the CAS line is driven low before RAS (normally an illegal operation), then the DRAM ignores the address inputs and uses an internal counter to select the row to open.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] This is known as CAS-before-RAS (CBR) refresh.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] This became the standard form of refresh for asynchronous DRAM, and is the only form generally used with SDRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Given support of CAS-before-RAS refresh, it is possible to deassert RAS while holding CAS low to maintain data output.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] If RAS is then asserted again, this performs a CBR refresh cycle while the DRAM outputs remain valid.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Because data output is not interrupted, this is known as *hidden refresh*.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Hidden refresh is no faster than a normal read followed by a normal refresh, but does maintain the data output valid during the refresh cycle.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Page mode DRAM was in turn later improved with a small modification which further reduced latency.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] DRAMs with this improvement are called **fast page mode DRAMs** (**FPM DRAMs**).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] In page mode DRAM, the chip does not capture the column address until CAS is asserted, so column access time (until data out was valid) begins when CAS is asserted.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] In FPM DRAM, the column address can be supplied while CAS is still deasserted, and the main column access time (*t*AA) begins as soon as the address is stable.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] The CAS signal is only needed to enable the output (the data out pins were held at high-Z while CAS was deasserted), so time from CAS assertion to data valid (*t*CAC) is greatly reduced.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Fast page mode DRAM was introduced in 1986 and was used with the Intel 80486.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Extended data out DRAM (EDO DRAM) was invented and patented in the 1990s by Micron Technology who then licensed technology to many other memory manufacturers.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] EDO RAM, sometimes referred to as *hyper page mode* enabled DRAM, is similar to fast page mode DRAM with the additional feature that a new access cycle can be started while keeping the data output of the previous cycle active.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] This can be used to overlap operations a certain amount (pipelining) and improve performance somewhat.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] It is up to 30% faster than FPM DRAM which it began to replace in 1995 when Intel introduced the 430FX chipset with EDO DRAM support.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Regardless of the performance gains, FPM and EDO SIMMs can be used interchangeably in many (but not all) applications.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] To be precise, EDO DRAM begins data output on the falling edge of CAS but does not disable the output when CAS rises again.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Instead, it holds the current output valid (thus extending the data output time) even as the DRAM begins decoding a new column address, until either a new column's data is selected by another CAS falling edge, or the output is switched off by the rising edge of RAS.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] EDO's capabilities were able to partially compensate for the performance lost due to the lack of an L2 cache in low-cost, commodity PCs.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] More expensive notebooks also often lacked an L2 cache due to size and power limitations, and benefitted similarly.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Even for systems *with* an L2 cache, the availability of EDO memory improved the average memory latency seen by applications over earlier FPM implementations.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Single-cycle EDO DRAM became very popular on video cards toward the end of the 1990s.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] It was very low cost, yet nearly as efficient for performance as the far more costly VRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] An evolution of EDO DRAM, burst EDO DRAM (BEDO DRAM), could process four memory addresses in one burst, for a maximum of 5-1-1-1, saving an additional three clocks over optimally designed EDO memory.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] It was done by adding an address counter on the chip to keep track of the next address.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] BEDO also added a pipeline stage allowing page-access cycle to be divided into two parts.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] During a memory-read operation, the first part accessed the data from the memory array to the output stage (second latch).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] The second part drove the data bus from this latch at the appropriate logic level.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Since the data is already in the output buffer, quicker access time is achieved (up to 50% for large blocks of data) than with traditional EDO.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Although BEDO DRAM showed additional optimization over EDO, by the time it was available the market had made a significant investment towards synchronous DRAM, or SDRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Even though BEDO RAM was superior to SDRAM in some ways, the latter technology quickly displaced BEDO.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Synchronous dynamic RAM (SDRAM) significantly revises the asynchronous memory interface, adding a clock (and a clock enable) line.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] All other signals are received on the rising edge of the clock.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] The OE line's function is extended to a per-byte DQM signal, which controls data input (writes) in addition to data output (reads).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] This allows DRAM chips to be wider than 8 bits while still supporting byte-granularity writes.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Many timing parameters remain under the control of the DRAM controller.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] For example, a minimum time must elapse between a row being activated and a read or write command.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] One important parameter must be programmed into the SDRAM chip itself, namely the CAS latency.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] This is the number of clock cycles allowed for internal operations between a read command and the first data word appearing on the data bus.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] The *Load mode register* command is used to transfer this value to the SDRAM chip.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Other configurable parameters include the length of read and write bursts, i.e. the number of words transferred per read or write command.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] The most significant change, and the primary reason that SDRAM has supplanted asynchronous RAM, is the support for multiple internal banks inside the DRAM chip.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Using a few bits of *bank address* that accompany each command, a second bank can be activated and begin reading data *while a read from the first bank is in progress*.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] By alternating banks, a single SDRAM device can keep the data bus continuously busy, in a way that asynchronous DRAM cannot.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Single data rate SDRAM (SDR SDRAM or SDR) is the original generation of SDRAM; it made a single transfer of data per clock cycle.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Double data rate SDRAM (DDR SDRAM or DDR) was a later development of SDRAM, used in PC memory beginning in 2000.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Subsequent specifications are numbered sequentially (*DDR2*, *DDR3*, etc.).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] DDR SDRAM internally performs double-width accesses at the clock rate, and uses a double data rate interface to transfer one half on each clock edge.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] DDR2 and DDR3 increased this factor to 4× and 8×, respectively, delivering 4-word and 8-word bursts over 2 and 4 clock cycles, respectively.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] The internal access rate is mostly unchanged (200 million per second for DDR-400, DDR2-800 and DDR3-1600 memory), but each access transfers more data.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Reduced Latency DRAM (RLDRAM) is a high performance double data rate (DDR) SDRAM that combines fast, random access with high bandwidth, mainly intended for networking and caching applications.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Graphics RAMs are asynchronous and synchronous DRAMs designed for graphics-related tasks such as texture memory and framebuffers, found on video cards.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Video DRAM (VRAM) is a dual-ported variant of DRAM that was once commonly used to store the frame buffer in some graphics adapters.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Window DRAM (WRAM) is a variant of VRAM that was once used in graphics adapters such as the Matrox Millennium and ATI 3D Rage Pro.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] WRAM was designed to perform better and cost less than VRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] WRAM offered up to 25% greater bandwidth than VRAM and accelerated commonly used graphical operations such as text drawing and block fills.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Multibank DRAM (MDRAM) is a type of specialized DRAM developed by MoSys.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] It is constructed from small memory banks of 256 kB, which are operated in an interleaved fashion, providing bandwidths suitable for graphics cards at a lower cost to memories such as SRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] MDRAM also allows operations to two banks in a single clock cycle, permitting multiple concurrent accesses to occur if the accesses were independent.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] MDRAM was primarily used in graphic cards, such as those featuring the Tseng Labs ET6x00 chipsets.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Boards based upon this chipset often had the unusual capacity of 2.25 MB because of MDRAM's ability to be implemented more easily with such capacities.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] A graphics card with 2.25 MB of MDRAM had enough memory to provide 24-bit color at a resolution of 1024 × 768—a very popular setting at the time.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Synchronous graphics RAM (SGRAM) is a specialized form of SDRAM for graphics adapters.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] It adds functions such as bit masking (writing to a specified bit plane without affecting the others) and block write (filling a block of memory with a single color).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Unlike VRAM and WRAM, SGRAM is single-ported.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] However, it can open two memory pages at once, which simulates the dual-port nature of other video RAM technologies.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Graphics double data rate SDRAM is a type of specialized DDR SDRAM designed to be used as the main memory of graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] GDDR SDRAM is distinct from commodity types of DDR SDRAM such as DDR3, although they share some core technologies.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Their primary characteristics are higher clock frequencies for both the DRAM core and I/O interface, which provides greater memory bandwidth for GPUs.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] As of 2025, there are eight successive generations of GDDR: GDDR2, GDDR3, GDDR4, GDDR5, GDDR5X, GDDR6, GDDR6X and GDDR7.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Pseudostatic RAM (PSRAM or PSDRAM) is dynamic RAM with built-in refresh and address-control circuitry to make it behave similarly to static RAM (SRAM).
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] It combines the high density of DRAM with the ease of use of true SRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] PSRAM was used in the Apple iPhone 3G and other embedded systems such as XFlar Platform.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Some DRAM components have a *self-refresh mode*.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] While this involves much of the same logic that is needed for pseudo-static operation, this mode is often equivalent to a standby mode.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] It is provided primarily to allow a system to suspend operation of its DRAM controller to save power without losing data stored in DRAM, rather than to allow operation without a separate DRAM controller as is in the case of mentioned PSRAMs.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] An embedded variant of PSRAM was sold by MoSys under the name 1T-SRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] It is a set of small DRAM banks with an SRAM cache in front to make it behave much like a true SRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] It is used in Nintendo GameCube and Wii video game consoles.
[src:rowhammer-defense/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Cypress Semiconductor's HyperRAM is a type of PSRAM supporting a JEDEC-compliant 8-pin HyperBus or Octal xSPI interface.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Typically, ECC memory maintains a memory system immune to single-bit errors: the data that is read from each word is always the same as the data that had been written to it, even if one of the bits actually stored has been flipped to the wrong state.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Most non-ECC memory cannot detect errors, although some non-ECC memory with parity support allows detection but not correction.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] ECC memory is used in most computers where data corruption cannot be tolerated, like industrial control applications, critical databases, and infrastructural memory caches.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Error correction codes protect against undetected data corruption and are used in computers where such corruption is unacceptable, examples being scientific and financial computing applications, or in database and file servers.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] ECC can also reduce the number of crashes in multi-user server applications and maximum-availability systems.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Electrical or magnetic interference inside a computer system can cause a single bit of dynamic random-access memory (DRAM) to spontaneously flip to the opposite state.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Hence, the error rates increase rapidly with rising altitude; for example, compared to sea level, the rate of neutron flux is 3.5 times higher at 1.5 km and 300 times higher at 10–12 km (the cruising altitude of commercial airplanes).
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] As a result, systems operating at high altitudes require special provisions for reliability.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] As an example, the spacecraft *Cassini–Huygens*, launched in 1997, contained two identical flight recorders, each with 2.5 gigabits of memory in the form of arrays of commercial DRAM chips.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Due to built-in EDAC functionality, the spacecraft's engineering telemetry reported the number of (correctable) single-bit-per-word errors and (uncorrectable) double-bit-per-word errors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] During the first 2.5 years of flight, the spacecraft reported a nearly constant single-bit error rate of about 280 errors per day.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] However, on November 6, 1997, during the first month in space, the number of errors increased by more than a factor of four on that single day.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] This was attributed to a solar particle event that had been detected by the satellite GOES 9.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] There was some concern that as DRAM density increases further, and thus the components on chips get smaller, while operating voltages continue to fall, DRAM chips will be affected by such radiation more frequently, since lower-energy particles will be able to change a memory cell's state.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] On the other hand, smaller cells make smaller targets, and moves to technologies such as SOI may make individual cells less susceptible and so counteract, or even reverse, this trend.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Recent studies show that single-event upsets due to cosmic radiation have been dropping dramatically with process geometry, and previous concerns over increasing bit cell error rates are unfounded.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Work published between 2007 and 2009 showed widely varying error rates with over 7 orders of magnitude difference, ranging from 10−10 error/(bit·h), roughly one bit error per hour per gigabyte of memory, to 10−17 error/(bit·h), roughly one bit error per millennium per gigabyte of memory.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] A large-scale study based on Google's very large number of servers was presented at the SIGMETRICS/Performance '09 conference.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] The actual error rate found was several orders of magnitude higher than the previous small-scale or laboratory studies, with between 25,000 (2.5×10−11 error/(bit·h)) and 70,000 (7.0×10−11 error/(bit·h), or 1 bit error per gigabyte of RAM per 1.8 hours) errors per billion device hours per megabit.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] More than 8% of DIMM memory modules were affected by errors per year.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] The consequence of a memory error is system-dependent.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] In systems without ECC, an error can lead either to a crash or to corruption of data; in large-scale production sites, memory errors are one of the most-common hardware causes of machine crashes.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Memory errors can cause security vulnerabilities.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] A memory error can have no consequences if it changes a bit which neither causes observable malfunctioning nor affects data used in calculations or saved.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] A 2010 simulation study showed that, for a web browser, only a small fraction of memory errors caused data corruption, although, as many memory errors are intermittent and correlated, the effects of memory errors were greater than would be expected for independent soft errors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Some tests conclude that the isolation of DRAM memory cells can be circumvented by unintended side effects of specially crafted accesses to adjacent cells.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Thus, accessing data stored in DRAM causes memory cells to leak their charges and interact electrically, as a result of high cell density in modern memory, altering the content of nearby memory rows that actually were not addressed in the original memory access.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] This effect is known as row hammer, and it has also been used in some privilege escalation computer security exploits.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Several approaches have been developed to deal with unwanted bit-flips, including immunity-aware programming, RAM parity memory, and ECC memory.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] This problem can be mitigated by using DRAM modules that include extra memory bits and memory controllers that exploit these bits.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] These extra bits are used to record parity or to use an error-correcting code (ECC).
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Parity allows the detection of all single-bit errors (actually, any odd number of wrong bits), but not correction, so the system has to either carry on (just flagging the problem) or halt.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Error-correction codes allow for more errors to be corrected; how much depends on the exact type of memory used.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] DRAM memory may provide increased protection against soft errors by relying on error-correcting codes.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Such error-correcting memory, known as *ECC* or *EDAC-protected* memory, is particularly desirable for highly fault-tolerant applications, such as servers, as well as deep-space applications due to increased radiation.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Some systems also "scrub" the memory, by periodically reading all addresses and writing back corrected versions if necessary to remove accumulated soft errors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Many early implementations of ECC memory, as well as on-die ECC, mask correctable errors, acting "as if" the error never occurred, and only report uncorrectable errors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Modern implementations log both correctable errors (CE) and uncorrectable errors (UE).
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Some people proactively replace memory modules that exhibit high error rates, in order to reduce the likelihood of uncorrectable error events.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Standard server memory are designed for a single-error correction and double-error detection (SECDED) Hamming code, which allows a single-bit error to be corrected and double-bit errors to be detected per word (the unit of bus transfer).
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Since DDR SDRAM, the standard bus width (word size) as far as memory is concerned is 64 bits.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] As a result, the typical setup between DDR and DDR4 is a 72-bit word with 64 data bits and 8 checking bits.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] DDR5 SDRAM splits the bus into two somewhat independent 32-bit subchannels, so ECC memory uses 80 bits of width in total, split between two 40-bit (32 data, 8 checking) channels.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] ECC is also used with smaller and larger sizes.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] An ECC-capable memory controller uses the additional bits to store the SECDED code; the memory is only responsible for holding the extra bits.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Since the late 1990s, the memory controller also communicates to the BIOS and maintains a count of errors detected and corrected, in part to help identify failing memory modules before the problem becomes catastrophic.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Reading the counter is supported on many systems thanks to the SMBIOS standard, being available on Linux, BSD, and Windows (Windows 2000 and later).
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Error detection and correction depends on an expectation of the kinds of errors that occur.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Implicitly, it is assumed that the failure of each bit in a word of memory is independent, resulting in improbability of two simultaneous errors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] This used to be the case when memory chips were one-bit wide, what was typical in the first half of the 1980s; later developments moved many bits into the same chip.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] This weakness is addressed by various technologies, including IBM's Chipkill, Sun Microsystems' Extended ECC, Hewlett-Packard's Chipspare, and Intel's Single Device Data Correction (SDDC), all of which make sure that the failure of one memory chip would only affect one bit per ECC word.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] This is achieved by scattering the bits of ECC words across chips, a form of interleaving.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] To make sure each chip only gets one bit per word, it may be necessary to interleave across multiple memory modules (sticks).
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Interleaving in general is a useful technique to defend against correlated multi-bit failures.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] A cosmic ray, for example, may upset multiple physically neighboring bits across multiple words by associating neighboring bits to different words.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] As long as a single-event upset (SEU) does not exceed the error threshold (e.g., a single error) in any particular word between accesses, it can be corrected (e.g., by a single-bit error-correcting code), and an effectively error-free memory system may be maintained.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Some DRAM chips include internal "on-chip" or "on-die" error-correction circuits, which allow systems with non-ECC memory controllers to still gain most of the benefits of ECC memory.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] In some systems, a similar effect may be achieved by using EOS memory modules.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] As mentioned above, on-die ECC is mandatory on DDR5 and LPDDR6.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] However, its lack of reporting means that very little is known about the true state of the memory chip until the errors exceed the ability for the on-die algorithm to perform correction; no information on how much "margin" there is conveyed.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Sophisticated algorithms have been built to infer the existence of corrected errors based on non-corrected errors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Many ECC memory systems use an "external" EDAC circuit between the CPU and the memory.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] A few systems with ECC memory use both internal and external EDAC systems; the external EDAC system should be designed to correct certain errors that the internal EDAC system is unable to correct.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Modern desktop and server CPUs integrate the EDAC circuit into the CPU, even before the shift toward CPU-integrated memory controllers, which are related to the NUMA architecture.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] CPU integration enables a zero-penalty EDAC system during error-free operation.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] As of 2009, the most-common error-correction codes use Hamming or Hsiao codes that provide single-bit error correction and double-bit error detection (SEC-DED).
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Other error-correction codes have been proposed for protecting memory – double-bit error correcting and triple-bit error detecting (DEC-TED) codes, single-nibble error correcting and double-nibble error detecting (SNC-DND) codes, Reed–Solomon error correction codes, etc.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] However, in practice, multi-bit correction is usually implemented by interleaving multiple SEC-DED codes.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Early research attempted to minimize the area and delay overheads of ECC circuits.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Hamming first demonstrated that SEC-DED codes were possible with one particular check matrix.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Hsiao showed that an alternative matrix with odd-weight columns provides SEC-DED capability with less hardware area and shorter delay than traditional Hamming SEC-DED codes.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] More recent research also attempts to minimize power in addition to minimizing area and delay.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Error-correcting memory controllers traditionally use space-optimal error-correction codes such as Hamming and Hsiao.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] If cost and space is not a concern but speed is, a triple modular redundancy (TMR) may be used due for its faster hardware implementation.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Space satellite systems often use TMR, although satellite RAM usually uses Hamming error correction.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Seymour Cray famously said "parity is for farmers" when asked why he left this out of the CDC 6600.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Later, he included parity in the CDC 7600, which caused pundits to remark that "apparently a lot of farmers buy computers".
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] The original IBM PC and all PCs until the early 1990s used parity checking.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Most data paths on a 2020s personal computer, including PCIe, SATA, chip-to-chip interconnection, and on-disk storage, have some form of ECC protection.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] The lack of ECC on main memory is in comparison unusual, especially given the size and higher likelihood of corruption.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Linus Torvalds wrote a long post in a forum in 2021 attacking Intel's choice to forgo ECC support on desktop platforms, when contemporary AMD desktop platforms could use (but not necessary enable the ECC feature on) registered DIMMs with ECC support.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Many CPUs use error-correction codes in the on-chip cache, including the Intel Itanium, Xeon, Core and Pentium (since P6 microarchitecture) processors, the AMD Athlon, Opteron, all Zen- and Zen+-based processors (EPYC, EPYC Embedded, Ryzen and Ryzen Threadripper), and the DEC Alpha 21264.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] As of 2006, EDC/ECC and ECC/ECC are the two most-common cache error-protection techniques used in commercial microprocessors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] The EDC/ECC technique uses an error-detecting code (EDC) in the level 1 cache.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] If an error is detected, data is recovered from ECC-protected level 2 cache.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] The ECC/ECC technique uses an ECC-protected level 1 cache and an ECC-protected level 2 cache.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] CPUs that use the EDC/ECC technique always write-through all STOREs to the level 2 cache, so that when an error is detected during a read from the level 1 data cache, a copy of that data can be recovered from the level 2 cache.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Registered, or buffered, memory is not the same as ECC; the technologies perform different functions.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] It is usual for memory used in servers to be both registered, to allow many memory modules to be used without electrical problems, and ECC, for data integrity.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] The use of ECC to increase data security often comes with a bigger expense, resulting in a marginally slower performance and higher memory costs.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] ECC memory is more expensive than non-ECC memory due to its additional error-checking functionality.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] The added extra cost of ECC memory for 1 GB in 2010 varies between $0 and $15, depending on performance and manufacturer.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] The design of ECC and its purpose in high-reliability workloads positioned it to have additional overhead for validation and the added extra circuit-level designs within the memory.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] The said features typically result in higher costs for the implementation of ECC.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Motherboard manufacturers may choose to add ECC compatibility of varying levels depending on the market segment.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] Some ECC-enabled boards and processors are able to support unbuffered (unregistered) ECC, but will also work with non-ECC memory; system firmware enables ECC functionality if ECC memory is installed.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] ECC may lower memory performance by around 2–3 percent on some systems, depending on the application and implementation, due to the additional time needed for ECC memory controllers to perform error checking.
[src:rowhammer-defense/ecc-memory] However, modern systems integrate ECC testing into the CPU, generating no additional delay to memory accesses as long as no errors are detected.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] In computing, telecommunication, information theory, and coding theory, **forward error correction** (**FEC**) or **channel coding** is a technique used for controlling errors in data transmission over unreliable or noisy communication channels.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The central idea is that the sender encodes the message in a redundant way, most often by using an **error correction code**, or **error correcting code** (**ECC**).
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The redundancy allows the receiver not only to detect errors that may occur anywhere in the message, but often to correct a limited number of errors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Therefore a reverse channel to request re-transmission may not be needed.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The cost is a fixed, higher forward channel bandwidth.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The American mathematician Richard Hamming pioneered this field in the 1940s and invented the first error-correcting code in 1950: the Hamming (7,4) code.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] FEC can be applied in situations where re-transmissions are costly or impossible, such as one-way communication links or when transmitting to multiple receivers in multicast.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Long-latency connections also benefit; in the case of satellites orbiting distant planets, retransmission due to errors would create a delay of several hours.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] FEC is also widely used in modems and in cellular networks.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] FEC processing in a receiver may be applied to a digital bit stream or in the demodulation of a digitally modulated carrier.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] For the latter, FEC is an integral part of the initial analog-to-digital conversion in the receiver.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The Viterbi decoder implements a soft-decision algorithm to demodulate digital data from an analog signal corrupted by noise.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Many FEC decoders can also generate a bit-error rate (BER) signal which can be used as feedback to fine-tune the analog receiving electronics.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] FEC information is added to mass storage (magnetic, optical and solid state/flash based) devices to enable recovery of corrupted data, and is used as ECC computer memory on systems that require special provisions for reliability.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The maximum proportion of errors or missing bits that can be corrected is determined by the design of the ECC, so different forward error correcting codes are suitable for different conditions.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] In general, a stronger code induces more redundancy that needs to be transmitted using the available bandwidth, which reduces the effective bit-rate while improving the received effective signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The noisy-channel coding theorem of Claude Shannon can be used to compute the maximum achievable communication bandwidth for a given maximum acceptable error probability.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] This establishes bounds on the theoretical maximum information transfer rate of a channel with some given base noise level.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] However, the proof is not constructive, and hence gives no insight of how to build a capacity achieving code.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] After years of research, some advanced FEC systems like polar code come very close to the theoretical maximum (Shannon limit) given by the Shannon channel capacity under the hypothesis of an infinite length frame.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] ECC is accomplished by adding redundancy to the transmitted information using an algorithm.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] A redundant bit may be a complicated function of many original information bits.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The original information may or may not appear literally in the encoded output; codes that include the unmodified input in the output are **systematic**, while those that do not are **non-systematic**.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] A simplistic example of ECC is to transmit each data bit three times, which is known as a (3,1) repetition code.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Through a noisy channel, a receiver might see eight versions of the output; see the table below.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] This allows an error in any one of the three samples to be corrected by "majority vote" or "democratic voting".
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Though simple to implement and widely used, this triple modular redundancy is a relatively inefficient ECC.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Better ECC codes typically examine the last several tens or even the last several hundreds of previously received bits to determine how to decode the current small handful of bits (typically in groups of two to eight bits).
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Most commonly, f is a homomorphism in the sense that if $x_{1}*x_{2}$ is the concatenation of $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ , then we have the following: $f(u_{1}*u_{2})=f(u_{1})*f(u_{2})$ This implies that it is enough to define $f(\sigma )$ for single-letter words $\sigma$ .
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] A code with distance d can detect errors on k bits as long as $k<d$ , and among those detected errors, the code can correct l -bit errors whenever $2l<d$ .
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] ECC could be said to work by "averaging noise"; since each data bit affects many transmitted symbols, the corruption of some symbols by noise usually allows the original user data to be extracted from the other, uncorrupted received symbols that also depend on the same user data.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Most telecommunication systems use a fixed channel code designed to tolerate the expected worst-case bit error rate, and then fail to work at all if the bit error rate is ever worse.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The two main categories of ECC codes are block codes and convolutional codes.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Classical block codes are usually decoded using **hard-decision** algorithms, which means that for every input and output signal a hard decision is made whether it corresponds to a one or a zero bit.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] In contrast, convolutional codes are typically decoded using **soft-decision** algorithms like the Viterbi, MAP or BCJR algorithms, which process (discretized) analog signals, and which allow for much higher error-correction performance than hard-decision decoding.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Nearly all classical block codes apply the algebraic properties of finite fields.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Hence classical block codes are often referred to as algebraic codes.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] There are many types of block codes; Reed–Solomon coding is noteworthy for its widespread use in compact discs, DVDs, and hard disk drives.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Other examples of classical block codes include Golay, BCH, Multidimensional parity, and Hamming codes.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Hamming ECC is commonly used to correct ECC memory and early SLC NAND flash memory errors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] This provides single-bit error correction and 2-bit error detection.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Hamming codes are only suitable for more reliable single-level cell (SLC) NAND.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Denser multi-level cell (MLC) NAND may use multi-bit correcting ECC such as BCH, Reed–Solomon, or LDPC.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] NOR flash typically does not use any error correction.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Low-density parity-check (LDPC) codes are a class of highly efficient linear block codes made from many single parity check (SPC) codes.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] They can provide performance very close to the channel capacity (the theoretical maximum) using an iterated soft-decision decoding approach, at linear time complexity in terms of their block length.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Practical implementations rely heavily on decoding the constituent SPC codes in parallel.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] LDPC codes were first introduced by Robert G.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Gallager in his PhD thesis in 1960, but due to the computational effort in implementing encoder and decoder and the introduction of Reed–Solomon codes, they were mostly ignored until the 1990s.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Other LDPC codes are standardized for wireless communication standards within 3GPP MBMS (see fountain codes).
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Turbo coding is an iterated soft-decoding scheme that combines two or more relatively simple convolutional codes and an interleaver to produce a block code that can perform to within a fraction of a decibel of the Shannon limit.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Predating LDPC codes in terms of practical application, they now provide similar performance.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] One of the earliest commercial applications of turbo coding was the CDMA2000 1x (TIA IS-2000) digital cellular technology developed by Qualcomm and sold by Verizon Wireless, Sprint, and other carriers.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] It is also used for the evolution of CDMA2000 1x specifically for Internet access, 1xEV-DO (TIA IS-856).
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Like 1x, EV-DO was developed by Qualcomm, and is sold by Verizon Wireless, Sprint, and other carriers (Verizon's marketing name for 1xEV-DO is *Broadband Access*, Sprint's consumer and business marketing names for 1xEV-DO are *Power Vision* and *Mobile Broadband*, respectively).
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] In contrast to classical block codes that often specify an error-detecting or error-correcting ability, many modern block codes such as LDPC codes lack such guarantees.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Instead, modern codes are evaluated in terms of their bit error rates.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Most forward error correction codes correct only bit-flips, but not bit-insertions or bit-deletions.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] In this setting, the Hamming distance is the appropriate way to measure the bit error rate.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] A few forward error correction codes are designed to correct bit-insertions and bit-deletions, such as Marker Codes and Watermark Codes.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The Levenshtein distance is a more appropriate way to measure the bit error rate when using such codes.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The fundamental principle of ECC is to add redundant bits in order to help the decoder to find out the true message that was encoded by the transmitter.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The code-rate of a given ECC system is defined as the ratio between the number of information bits and the total number of bits (i.e., information plus redundancy bits) in a given communication package.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] A low code-rate close to zero implies a strong code that uses many redundant bits to achieve a good performance, while a large code-rate close to 1 implies a weak code.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The redundant bits that protect the information have to be transferred using the same communication resources that they are trying to protect.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] This causes a fundamental tradeoff between reliability and data rate.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] In one extreme, a strong code (with low code-rate) can induce an important increase in the receiver SNR (signal-to-noise-ratio) decreasing the bit error rate, at the cost of reducing the effective data rate.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] On the other extreme, not using any ECC (i.e., a code-rate equal to 1) uses the full channel for information transfer purposes, at the cost of leaving the bits without any additional protection.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] One interesting question is the following: how efficient in terms of information transfer can an ECC be that has a negligible decoding error rate?
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] This question was answered by Claude Shannon with his second theorem, which says that the channel capacity is the maximum bit rate achievable by any ECC whose error rate tends to zero: His proof relies on Gaussian random coding, which is not suitable to real-world applications.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The upper bound given by Shannon's work inspired a long journey in designing ECCs that can come close to the ultimate performance boundary.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Various codes today can attain almost the Shannon limit.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] However, capacity achieving ECCs are usually extremely complex to implement.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The most popular ECCs have a trade-off between performance and computational complexity.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Usually, their parameters give a range of possible code rates, which can be optimized depending on the scenario.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Usually, this optimization is done in order to achieve a low decoding error probability while minimizing the impact to the data rate.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Another criterion for optimizing the code rate is to balance low error rate and retransmissions number in order to the energy cost of the communication.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Sometimes it is only necessary to decode single bits of the message, or to check whether a given signal is a codeword, and do so without looking at the entire signal.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] This can make sense in a streaming setting, where codewords are too large to be classically decoded fast enough and where only a few bits of the message are of interest for now.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Also such codes have become an important tool in computational complexity theory, e.g., for the design of probabilistically checkable proofs.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Locally decodable codes are error-correcting codes for which single bits of the message can be probabilistically recovered by only looking at a small (say constant) number of positions of a codeword, even after the codeword has been corrupted at some constant fraction of positions.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Locally testable codes are error-correcting codes for which it can be checked probabilistically whether a signal is close to a codeword by only looking at a small number of positions of the signal.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Not all locally decodable codes (LDCs) are locally testable codes (LTCs) neither locally correctable codes (LCCs), q-query LCCs are bounded exponentially while LDCs can have subexponential lengths.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Single pass decoding with this family of error correction codes can yield very low error rates, but for long range transmission conditions (like deep space) iterative decoding is recommended.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Concatenated codes have been standard practice in satellite and deep space communications since Voyager 2 first used the technique in its 1986 encounter with Uranus.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The Galileo craft used iterative concatenated codes to compensate for the very high error rate conditions caused by having a failed antenna.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Interleaving is frequently used in digital communication and storage systems to improve the performance of forward error correcting codes.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Many communication channels are not memoryless: errors typically occur in bursts rather than independently.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] If the number of errors within a code word exceeds the error-correcting code's capability, it fails to recover the original code word.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Interleaving alleviates this problem by shuffling source symbols across several code words, thereby creating a more uniform distribution of errors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Therefore, interleaving is widely used for burst error-correction.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The analysis of modern iterated codes, like turbo codes and LDPC codes, typically assumes an independent distribution of errors.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Systems using LDPC codes therefore typically employ additional interleaving across the symbols within a code word.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] For turbo codes, an interleaver is an integral component and its proper design is crucial for good performance.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The iterative decoding algorithm works best when there are not short cycles in the factor graph that represents the decoder; the interleaver is chosen to avoid short cycles.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] In multi-carrier communication systems, interleaving across carriers may be employed to provide frequency diversity, e.g., to mitigate frequency-selective fading or narrowband interference.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Here, each group of the same letter represents a 4-bit one-bit error-correcting codeword.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The codeword cccc is altered in one bit and can be corrected, but the codeword dddd is altered in three bits, so either it cannot be decoded at all or it might be decoded incorrectly.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] In each of the codewords "aaaa", "eeee", "ffff", and "gggg", only one bit is altered, so one-bit error-correcting code will decode everything correctly.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The term "AnExample" ends up mostly unintelligible and difficult to correct.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] No word is completely lost and the missing letters can be recovered with minimal guesswork.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Use of interleaving techniques increases total delay.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] This is because the entire interleaved block must be received before the packets can be decoded.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Also interleavers hide the structure of errors; without an interleaver, more advanced decoding algorithms can take advantage of the error structure and achieve more reliable communication than a simpler decoder combined with an interleaver.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] An example of such an algorithm is based on neural network structures.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] Simulating the behaviour of error-correcting codes (ECCs) in software is a common practice to design, validate and improve ECCs.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The upcoming wireless 5G standard raises a new range of applications for the software ECCs: the Cloud Radio Access Networks (C-RAN) in a Software-defined radio (SDR) context.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] The idea is to directly use software ECCs in the communications.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] For instance in the 5G, the software ECCs could be located in the cloud and the antennas connected to this computing resources: improving this way the flexibility of the communication network and eventually increasing the energy efficiency of the system.
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] In this context, there are various available Open-source software listed below (non exhaustive).
[src:rowhammer-defense/error-correction-code] In the table above, for an error-correcting code of minimal Hamming distance d , the maximum number of errors that the code can detect is given by $d-1$ while the maximal number of errors that it can correct is given by $\left\lfloor {\frac {d-1}{2}}\right\rfloor$ .
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] In a DRAM chip, each bit of memory data is stored as the presence or absence of an electric charge on a small capacitor on the chip.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] As time passes, the charges in the memory cells leak away, so without being refreshed, the stored data would eventually be lost.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] To prevent this, external circuitry periodically reads each cell and rewrites it, restoring the charge on the capacitor to its original level.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Each **memory refresh cycle** refreshes a succeeding area of memory cells, thus repeatedly refreshing all the cells on the chip in a consecutive cycle.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] This process is typically conducted automatically in the background by the memory circuitry and is transparent to the user.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] While a refresh cycle is occurring, the memory is not available for normal read and write operations, but in modern memory, this overhead is not large enough to significantly slow down memory operation.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Static random-access memory (SRAM) is electronic memory that does not require refreshing.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] An SRAM memory cell requires four to six transistors, compared to a single transistor and a capacitor for DRAM; therefore, SRAM circuits require more area on a chip.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] As a result, data density is much lower in SRAM chips than in DRAM, which gives SRAM a higher price per bit.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Therefore, DRAM is used for the main memory in computers, video game consoles, graphics cards and applications requiring large capacities and low cost.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] The need for memory refresh makes DRAM more complicated, but the density and cost advantages of DRAM justify this complexity.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] While the memory is operating, each memory cell must be refreshed repetitively and within the maximum interval between refreshes specified by the manufacturer, usually in the millisecond region.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Refreshing does not employ the normal memory operations (read and write cycles) used to access data, but specialized cycles called *refresh cycles* which are generated by separate counter circuits and interspersed between normal memory accesses.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] The storage cells on a memory chip are laid out in a rectangular array of rows and columns.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] The read process in DRAM is *destructive* and removes the charge on the memory cells in an entire row, so there is a column of specialized latches on the chip called sense amplifiers, one for each column of memory cells, to temporarily hold the data.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] During a normal read operation, the sense amplifiers, after reading and latching the data, rewrite the data in the accessed row.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] This arrangement allows the normal read electronics on the chip to refresh an entire row of memory in parallel, significantly speeding up the refresh process.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Although a normal read or write cycle refreshes a row of memory, normal memory accesses cannot be relied on to hit all the rows within the necessary time, necessitating a separate refresh process.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Rather than use the normal read cycle in the refresh process, to save time, an abbreviated refresh cycle is used.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] To ensure that each cell gets refreshed within the refresh time interval, the refresh circuitry must perform a refresh cycle on each of the rows on the chip within the interval.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] So in modern systems, refresh is handled by circuits in the memory controller, which may be embedded in the chip itself.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Specialized DRAM chips, such as pseudostatic RAM (PSRAM), have all the refresh circuitry on the chip, and function like static RAM as far as the rest of the computer is concerned.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Some early microprocessors (e.g., the Zilog Z80) provided special internal registers that could provide the Row Address Strobe (RAS) to refresh dynamic memory cells, the register being incremented on each refresh cycle.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] This could also be accomplished by other integrated circuits already being used in the system, if these already generate cycling accesses across RAM (e.g., the Motorola 6845).
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] In CPUs such as the Z80, the availability of a RAS refresh was a big selling point due to its simplifying hardware design.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Here, RAS refresh is signaled by a unique combination of address and control wires during operationally redundant clock cycles (T-States), i.e., during instruction decode and execution when the buses may not be required.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Instead of the bus being inactive during such T-states, the refresh register would be presented on the address bus along with a combination of control signals to activate the refresh circuitry.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] In early versions of the Z80, the ubiquity of 16 kB RAM chips having 128 rows and something of a lack of foresight resulted in the R register only incrementing over a 7-bit-wide range (0–127, 128 rows); the 8th bit could be set by the user, but would be left unchanged by the internal cycling.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] With the advent of 64 kbit+ DRAM chips (with 256 rows), extra circuitry or logic had to be built around the refresh signal to synthesize the missing 8th bit and prevent blocks of memory contents from being lost after a few milliseconds.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] In some contexts, it was possible to utilize interrupts and software to flip the 8th bit at the appropriate time and thus cover the entire range of the R register (256 rows).
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Another method, perhaps more universal but also more complex in terms of hardware, was to use an 8-bit counter chip, whose output would provide the refresh RAS address instead of the R register.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] The refresh signal from the CPU was used as the clock for this counter, resulting in the memory row being incremented with each refresh cycle.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Later versions and licensed work-alikes of the Z80 core remedied the non-inclusion of the 8th bit in automatic cycling, and modern CPUs have greatly expanded on such basic provisioning to provide rich, all-in-one solutions for DRAM refresh.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Pseudostatic RAM (PSRAM or PSDRAM) is dynamic RAM with built-in refresh and address-control circuitry to make it behave similarly to SRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] PSRAM (made by Numonyx) is used in the Apple iPhone and other embedded systems.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Some DRAM components have a self-refresh standby mode.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] It is provided primarily to allow a system to suspend operation of its DRAM controller to save power without losing data stored in DRAM, whereas PSRAM allows operation without a separate DRAM controller.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] An embedded variant of PSRAM is sold by MoSys under the name 1T-SRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] It is technically DRAM, but behaves much like SRAM, and is used in the GameCube and Wii consoles.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Usually, the refresh circuitry consists of a *refresh counter* which contains the address of the row to be refreshed, which is applied to the chip's row address lines, and a timer that increments the counter to step through the rows.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] This counter may be part of the memory controller circuitry or on the memory chip itself.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Burst refresh results in long periods when the memory is unavailable, so distributed refresh has been used in most modern systems, particularly in real-time systems.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] For example, DDR SDRAM has a refresh time of 64 ms and 8,192 rows, so the refresh cycle interval is 7.8 μs.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] In modern DDRx devices, only the distributed option is supported.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] On the other hand, LPDDRx devices still support burst refresh.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Synchronous DRAMs sample command and address signals on the edge of a clock.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] For example, an SDRAM chip has 213=8,192 rows, a refresh interval of 64 ms, the memory bus runs at 133 MHz, and the refresh cycle takes 4 clock cycles.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] So less than 0.4% of the memory chip's time will be taken by refresh cycles.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] In SDRAM chips, the memory in each chip is divided into banks which are refreshed in parallel, saving further time.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] So the number of refresh cycles needed is the number of rows in a single bank, given in the specifications, which in the 2012 generation of chips has been frozen at 8,192.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] The maximum time interval between refresh operations is standardized by JEDEC for each DRAM technology and is specified in the manufacturer's chip specifications.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] It is usually in the range of milliseconds for DRAM and microseconds for eDRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Maximum refresh interval depends on the ratio of charge stored in the memory cell capacitors to leakage currents.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Because the leakage currents in semiconductors increase with temperature, refresh intervals must be decreased at high temperatures.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] DDR2 SDRAM chips have a temperature-compensated refresh structure; refresh interval must be halved when chip case temperature exceeds 85 °C (185 °F).
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Although the geometry of the capacitors has been shrinking with each new generation of memory chips, reducing the charge stored, refresh intervals for DRAM have been increasing; from 8 ms for 1M chips, 32 ms for 16M chips, to 64 ms for 256M chips.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Longer refresh interval means a smaller fraction of the device's time is occupied with refresh, leaving more time for memory accesses.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] This improvement is achieved mainly by reduced leakage.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] The actual persistence of readable charge values and thus data in most DRAM memory cells is much longer than the refresh interval, up to 1–10 seconds.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] However, transistor leakage currents vary widely between different memory cells on the same chip due to process variation.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] In order to make sure that all the memory cells are refreshed before a single bit is lost, manufacturers must set their refresh times conservatively short.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] This frequent DRAM refresh consumes a third of the total power drawn by low-power electronics devices in standby mode.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Researchers have proposed several approaches for extending battery run-time between charges by reducing the refresh rate, including temperature-compensated refresh (TCR) and retention-aware placement in DRAM (RAPID).
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Experiments show that in a typical off-the-shelf DRAM chip, only a few weak cells really require the worst-case 64 ms refresh interval, and even then only at the high end of its specified temperature range.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] 24 °C (75 °F)), those same weak cells need to be refreshed once every 500 ms for correct operation.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] If the system can avoid using the weakest 1% of pages, a typical DRAM only needs to be refreshed once a second, even at 70 °C (158 °F), for correct operation of the remaining 99% of the pages.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Some experiments combine these two complementary techniques, giving correct operation at room temperature at refresh intervals of 10 seconds.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] For error-tolerant applications (e.g. graphics applications), refreshing non-critical data stored in DRAM or eDRAM at a rate lower than their retention period saves energy with minor quality loss, which is an example of approximate computing.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] In static random-access memory (SRAM), another type of semiconductor memory, the data is not stored as charge on a capacitor, but in a bistable circuit, so SRAM does not need to be refreshed.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] The two basic types of memory have advantages and disadvantages.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Static memory can be considered permanent while powered on, i.e., once written, the memory stays until specifically changed, and thus, its use tends to be simple in terms of system design.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] However, the internal construction of each SRAM cell requires six transistors, compared to the single transistor required for a DRAM cell, so the density of SRAM is much lower and price-per-bit much higher than DRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Several early computer memory technologies also required periodical processes similar in purpose to memory refresh.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] The Williams tube has the closest similarity, since, like DRAM, it is essentially a capacitive memory in which the values stored for each bit would gradually decay unless refreshed.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] In magnetic-core memory, each memory cell can retain data indefinitely even with the power turned off, but reading the data from any memory cell erases its contents.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] As a consequence, the memory controller typically added a refresh cycle after each read cycle in order to create the illusion of a non-destructive read operation.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Some early computers implemented atomic read–modify–write cycles (combined read and write with modify) for increment and decrement.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] Delay-line memory requires constant refreshing because the data is actually stored as a signal in a transmission line.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] In this case, the refresh rate is comparable to the memory access time.
[src:rowhammer-defense/memory-refresh] NAND flash memory may need a form of memory refresh to detect and correct ECC errors, especially if the memory has not been powered up in a long time.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] The Rowhammer effect has been used in some privilege escalation computer security exploits, and network-based attacks are also theoretically possible.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Different hardware-based techniques exist to prevent the Rowhammer effect from occurring, including required support in some processors and types of DRAM memory modules.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] In dynamic RAM (DRAM), each bit of stored data occupies a separate memory cell that is electrically implemented with one capacitor and one transistor.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] The charge state of a capacitor (charged or discharged) is what determines whether a DRAM cell stores "1" or "0" as a binary value.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Huge numbers of DRAM memory cells are packed into integrated circuits, together with some additional logic that organizes the cells for the purposes of reading, writing, and refreshing the data.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Memory cells (blue squares in both illustrations) are further organized into matrices and addressed through rows and columns.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] A memory address applied to a matrix is broken into the row address and column address, which are processed by the row and column address decoders (in both illustrations, vertical and horizontal green rectangles, respectively).
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Consequently, read operations are of a destructive nature because the design of DRAM requires memory cells to be rewritten after their values have been read by transferring the cell charges into the row buffer.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Write operations decode the addresses in a similar way, but as a result of the design entire rows must be rewritten for the value of a single bit to be changed.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] As a result of storing data bits using capacitors that have a natural discharge rate, DRAM memory cells lose their state over time and require periodic rewriting of all memory cells, a process known as refreshing.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] As another result of the design, DRAM memory is susceptible to random changes in stored data, which are known as soft memory errors and attributed to cosmic rays and other causes.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] There are different techniques that counteract soft memory errors and improve the reliability of DRAM, of which error-correcting code (ECC) memory and its advanced variants (such as lockstep memory) are most commonly used.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Increased densities of DRAM integrated circuits have led to physically smaller memory cells containing less charge, resulting in lower operational noise margins, increased rates of electromagnetic interactions between memory cells, and greater possibility of data loss.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] As a result, *disturbance errors* have been observed, being caused by cells interfering with each other's operation and manifesting as random changes in the values of bits stored in affected memory cells.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] However, researchers proved in a 2014 analysis that commercially available DDR3 SDRAM chips manufactured in 2012 and 2013 are susceptible to disturbance errors, while using the term *Rowhammer* to name the associated side effect that led to observed bit flips.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] The opportunity for the Rowhammer effect to occur in DDR3 memory is primarily attributed to DDR3's high density of memory cells and the results of associated interactions between the cells, while rapid DRAM row activations have been determined as the primary cause.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Tests show that a disturbance error may be observed after performing around 139,000 subsequent memory row accesses (with cache flushes), and that up to one memory cell in every 1,700 cells may be susceptible.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Those tests also show that the rate of disturbance errors is not substantially affected by increased environment temperature, while it depends on the actual contents of DRAM because certain bit patterns result in significantly higher disturbance error rates.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Tests show that this approach may result in a significantly higher rate of disturbance errors, compared to the variant that activates only one of the victim row's neighboring DRAM rows.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] As DRAM vendors have deployed mitigations, patterns had to become more sophisticated to bypass Rowhammer mitigations.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] More recent Rowhammer patterns include non-uniform, frequency-based patterns.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] These patterns consist of many double-sided aggressors pairs where each of them is hammered with a different frequency, phase, and amplitude.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Using this and synchronizing patterns with the REFRESH command, it is possible to very effectively determine "blind spots" where the mitigation is not able to provide protection anymore.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Based on this idea, academics built a Rowhammer fuzzer named *Blacksmith* that can bypass existing mitigations on all DDR4 devices.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Different methods exist for more or less successful detection, prevention, correction or mitigation of the Rowhammer effect.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Tests show that simple error correction code, providing single-error correction and double-error detection (SECDED) capabilities, are not able to correct or detect all observed disturbance errors because some of them include more than two flipped bits per memory word.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Furthermore, research shows that precisely targeted three-bit Rowhammer flips prevents ECC memory from noticing the modifications.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] A less effective solution is to introduce more frequent memory refreshing, with the refresh intervals shorter than the usual 64 ms, but this technique results in higher power consumption and increased processing overhead; some vendors provide firmware updates that implement this type of mitigation.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Research shows that these two prevention measures cause negligible performance impacts.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] When used with DIMMs that are not pTRR-compliant, these Xeon processors by default fall back on performing DRAM refreshes at twice the usual frequency, which results in slightly higher memory access latency and may reduce the memory bandwidth by up to 2–4%.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] The LPDDR4 mobile memory standard published by JEDEC includes optional hardware support for the so-called *target row refresh* (TRR) that prevents the Rowhammer effect without negatively impacting performance or power consumption.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Additionally, some manufacturers implement TRR in their DDR4 products, although it is not part of the DDR4 memory standard published by JEDEC.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Internally, TRR identifies possible victim rows, by counting the number of row activations and comparing it against predefined chip-specific *maximum activate count* (MAC) and *maximum activate window* (tMAW) values, and refreshes these rows to prevent bit flips.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Research showed that TRR mitigations deployed on DDR4 UDIMMs and LPDDR4X chips from devices produced between 2019 and 2020 are not effective in protecting against Rowhammer.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Due to their necessity of huge numbers of rapidly performed DRAM row activations, Rowhammer exploits issue large numbers of uncached memory accesses that cause cache misses, which can be detected by monitoring the rate of cache misses for unusual peaks using hardware performance counters.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Version 5.0 of the MemTest86 memory diagnostic software, released on December 3, 2013, added a Rowhammer test that checks whether computer RAM is susceptible to disturbance errors, but it only works if the computer boots UEFI; without UEFI, it boots an older version with no hammer test.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Memory protection, as a way of preventing processes from accessing memory that has not been assigned to each of them, is one of the concepts behind most modern operating systems.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Using privilege separation can also reduce the extent of potential damage caused by computer security attacks by restricting their effects to specific parts of the system.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] In comparison, "conventional" attack vectors such as buffer overflows aim at circumventing the protection mechanisms at the software level, by exploiting various programming mistakes to achieve alterations of otherwise inaccessible main memory contents.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] The initial research into the Rowhammer effect, published and presented in June 2014 at the International Symposium on Computer Architecture, described and analyzed the nature of DRAM read disturbance errors in DDR3 DRAM chips.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] This paper experimentally studied 129 real DDR3 DRAM modules from three DRAM manufacturers and demonstrated read disturbance bitflips in 110 of them.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] It also showed that a user-level program run on two real systems from Intel and AMD induces bitflips in main memory.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] The work indicated the potential for constructing an attack, saying that "With some engineering effort, we believe we can develop Code 1a into a disturbance attack that injects errors into other programs, crashes the system, or perhaps even hijacks control of the system.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] A subsequent October 2014 research paper did not imply the existence of any security-related issues arising from the Rowhammer effect.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] On March 9, 2015, Google's Project Zero revealed two working privilege escalation exploits based on the Rowhammer effect, establishing its exploitable nature on the x86-64 architecture.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] One of the revealed exploits targets the Google Native Client (NaCl) mechanism for running a limited subset of x86-64 machine instructions within a sandbox, exploiting the Rowhammer effect to escape from the sandbox and gain the ability to issue system calls directly.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] This NaCl vulnerability, tracked as CVE-2015-0565, has been mitigated by modifying the NaCl so it does not allow execution of the `clflush` (cache line flush) machine instruction, which was previously believed to be required for constructing an effective Rowhammer attack.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] The second exploit revealed by Project Zero runs as an unprivileged Linux process on the x86-64 architecture, exploiting the Rowhammer effect to gain unrestricted access to all physical memory installed in a computer.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] By combining the disturbance errors with memory spraying, this exploit is capable of altering page table entries used by the virtual memory system for mapping virtual addresses to physical addresses, which results in the exploit gaining unrestricted memory access.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Due to its nature and the inability of the x86-64 architecture to make `clflush` a privileged machine instruction, this exploit can hardly be mitigated on computers that do not use hardware with built-in Rowhammer prevention mechanisms.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] In July 2015, a group of security researchers published a paper that describes an architecture- and instruction-set-independent way for exploiting the Rowhammer effect.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Instead of relying on the `clflush` instruction to perform cache flushes, this approach achieves uncached memory accesses by causing a very high rate of cache eviction using carefully selected memory access patterns.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] Although the cache replacement policies differ between processors, this approach overcomes the architectural differences by employing an adaptive cache eviction strategy algorithm.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] The proof of concept for this approach is provided both as a native code implementation, and as a pure JavaScript implementation that runs on Firefox 39.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] The JavaScript implementation, called *Rowhammer.js*, uses large typed arrays and relies on their internal allocation using large pages; as a result, it demonstrates a very high-level exploit of a very low-level vulnerability.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] In October 2016, researchers published DRAMMER, an Android application that uses Rowhammer, together with other methods, to reliably gain root access on several popular smartphones.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] The vulnerability was acknowledged as CVE-2016-6728 and a mitigation was released by Google within a month.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] However, due to the general nature of possible implementations of the attack, an effective software patch is difficult to be reliably implemented.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] As of June 2018, most patch proposals made by academia and industry were either impractical to deploy or insufficient in stopping all attacks.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] As a mitigation, researchers proposed a lightweight defense that prevents attacks based on direct memory access (DMA) by isolating DMA buffers with guard rows.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] In May 2020, the TRRespass work showed that existing DDR4 DRAM chips, which are claimed to be protected and resilient against Rowhammer, are actually vulnerable to Rowhammer.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] This work introduced a new access pattern, called many-sided hammering, which circumvents Rowhammer protections that were put into place inside DDR4 DRAM chips.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] In May 2021, a Google research team announced a new exploit, Half-Double that takes advantage of the worsening physics of some of the newer DRAM chips.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] In March 2024, a group of researchers at ETH Zürich announced ZenHammer, a rowhammer exploit for AMD Zen chips, and also announced the first use of rowhammer to exploit DDR5 SDRAM.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] In June 2024, a group of researchers at ETH Zürich announced RISC-H, a rowhammer exploit for RISC-V chips, this is the first Rowhammer study on RISC-V.
[src:rowhammer-defense/row-hammer] In September 2025, a group of researchers at ETH Zürich announced Phoenix, which successfully bypassed all Rowhammer *Target Row Refresh* mitigations in one of the largest DDR5 SDRAM manufacturer's sample by using longer and more advanced patterns, and demonstrated the vulnerability in practice.
